Wash and dry produce.

In a #small pot{}, combine @Jasmine Rice{1/2%cup}, @water{3/4%cup}, and a
pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook
until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready
to serve.

Thinly slice @Scallions{2}(thinly sliced), separating whites from greens.
Quarter @Lime{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high
heat. Add shrimp and cook, stirring frequently, until cooked through,
~{4-6%minutes}. TIP: If there's excess grease in your pan, carefully pour it
out.

> Rinse shrimp under cold water; pat dry with paper towels. Swap in shrimp or
> beef for pork.

Stir scallion whites and @Shredded Red Cabbage{4%oz} into pan; cook, stirring
occasionally, until just tender, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in @Hoisin Sauce{2%tbsp}, @Sweet Thai Chili Sauce{1%oz},
@Sweet Soy Glaze{2 1/2%tbsp}, and @Sugar{1/2%tsp} until thoroughly combined.
Turn off heat.

> We sent more Sweet Soy Glaze - 5 TBSP for 4 servings; use 2 1/2 TBSP for 2
> servings. For 4 servings, use 1 tsp sugar instead of 1/2 tsp.

Taste and season with juice from half the lime, @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Fluff rice with a #fork{} and stir in @Butter{1%tbsp} until melted. Season with
salt and pepper.

Divide rice between #bowls{} and top with moo shu shrimp. Sprinkle with
scallion greens and as many @Sesame Seeds{1%tbsp} as you like. Serve with
any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.